<br>
However, I interpreted his/her comments as a direct afront to my beliefs. Looking back perhaps they were not intended to be so, but I maintain that my interpretation is really the only method of interpreting the comments at that time. What we apparently had was a strong mis-communication.<br>
<br>
You must understand, I have experienced statements like this before,<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Personally, I don't need a Catholic dictionary to define baptism. It seems quite clear what the Bible says.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
and given the context, I think my definition of it as &quot;anti-intellectual pride&quot; is accurate from my interpretation of what you meant. You seemed to have off-handedly dismissed the scholarship I was presenting. I really can't be certain if it was &quot;pride&quot; that makes you do this (or ignorance, or a familiarity with the topic), but from a Catholic perspective, the protestant notion of sola scriptura is rooted in pride (the &quot;I don't need anyones help, I know religion&quot; attitude (which incidently mirrors your statement almost verbatum)). Pride is the opposite of humble submission/obedience.<br>
<br>
As for my comments about pride and strenuous activity (reading an article), it really gets my goat when someone dismisses an entire article for no good reason other than, &quot;I already know, I don't need anyone to help me&quot; which I (mistakenly) thought you were espousing. That to me is the pinnacle of pride, the attitude that scholarship is useless and thus I don't need to inform myself because I already know. How much better the world would be if that attitude was eradicated.<br>
<br>
my comment:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Better hop into the BBQ darkhamster to get baptized.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Was obviously intended tongue in cheek. Matthew clearly says Jesus will come baptizing &quot;in the Holy Ghost and fire.&quot; This was an attempt to show that, contrary to darkmaster's claims, the Bible is not &quot;clear&quot; on what baptism is. I would hate to think of some fundamentalist biblical literalists burning themselves in the name of the Father and Son and Holy Spirit.<br>
<br>
But I have mentioned context a few times, and the first set of statements I would probably not have interpreted so harshly if they were not followed by what I perceived as a non sequitor attack directed against the Catholic Church, <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Notice that Jesus &quot;went up&quot; out of the water. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>This rules out</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> so-called sprinkling.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
